<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="277" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,260,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="277">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name comes from Latin prefix 
<emphasis box="[863,894,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="277">bi-</emphasis>
meaning “two”, and Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[1335,1436,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="277">caudatus</emphasis>
meaning “having a tail,” thus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sun" authorityYear="2016" box="[495,607,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Rhyacophilidae" genus="Rhyacophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicaudata">
<emphasis box="[495,607,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="277">bicaudata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning “two-tailed,” in reference to the preanal appendages extending beyond the apicodorsal lobe, giving an appearance of two tails in dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
